📊 Credit Risk Analysis & Decision Model

A Data Science project for credit risk evaluation using Logistic Regression and Machine Learning.

🚀 Overview

This project develops a predictive model to determine whether a client should be granted credit, based on socioeconomic and financial variables.

The dataset contains information on 700 clients, classified as:

1 → Credit denied (default)
0 → Credit approved

The main objective is to build a data-driven decision rule that optimizes credit allocation and reduces financial risk.

🎯 Objectives
Build an interpretable model for credit risk analysis
Identify key variables influencing credit decisions
Develop a predictive model for new clients
Evaluate performance from two perspectives:
Explanatory (in-sample)
Predictive (out-of-sample)
📂 Dataset

The dataset includes the following variables:

Variable	Description
x1	Age (years)
x2	Education level (1–5)
x3	Years with current employer
x4	Years at current address
x5	Household income (thousands)
x6	Debt-to-income ratio
x7	Credit card debt (thousands)
x8	Other debt (thousands)
x9	Previous default history
default	Target variable (1 = denied, 0 = approved)
⚙️ Methodology
1. Logistic Regression
Interpretable baseline model
Estimates probability of default
Analyzes the impact of each variable
2. Machine Learning Models
Comparison of predictive models
Performance optimization
Evaluation on unseen data
📏 Model Evaluation
🔍 Explanatory Analysis (Full Sample)

Model fit evaluation using:

Accuracy
Confusion Matrix
Sensitivity (Recall)
Specificity

Note: These metrics are used only as a measure of model fit.

🚀 Predictive Analysis (New Data)

Evaluation on test data:

Accuracy
Precision / Recall
F1-score
ROC-AUC
